{"title_page": "Religion in Lebanon", "text_new": "{{Pie chart\n|thumb = right\n|caption = Religion in Lebanon in 2012 by Statistics Lebanon<ref name=\"state2012\"/>\n|label1 = [[Sunni Islam]]\n|value1 = 27\n|color1 = LightGreen\n|label2 = [[Shia Islam]]\n|value2 = 27\n|color2 = DarkGreen\n|label3 = [[Maronite Church|Maronite Catholicism]]\n|value3 = 21\n|color3 = Red\n|label4 = [[Melkite Greek Catholic Church|Greek Catholicism]]\n|value4 = 5\n|color4 = Yellow\n|label5 = [[Greek Orthodox Church of Antioch|Greek Orthodoxy]]\n|value5 = 8\n|color5 = Purple\n|label6 = Other Christian ([[Armenian Apostolic Church|Armenian Apostolic]] and others)\n|value6 = 6.5\n|color6 = DarkBlue\n|label7 = [[Druze]]\n|value7 = 5.6\n|color7 = Violet\n|label8 = Other\n|value8 = 1\n|color8 = Black\n}}\n'''[[Lebanon]]''' is an eastern Mediterranean country that is composed of mostly [[Muslim Arabs|Muslims]] and [[Christians]].<ref name=\"cia\" />   The main two religions are [[Islam in Lebanon|Islam]] with 50% of the citizens ([[Sunni Islam in Lebanon|Sunni]] and [[Shia Islam in Lebanon|Shia]]) and [[Christianity in Lebanon|Christianity]] with 44.4% of the citizens (the [[Maronite Christianity in Lebanon|Maronite Church]], the [[Greek Orthodox Christianity in Lebanon|Orthodox Church]], the [[Melkite Greek Catholic Church]], the [[Protestantism in Lebanon|Protestant Church]], the [[Armenian Apostolic Church]]). The [[Druze in Lebanon|Druze]] are about 4.9% of the citizens.<ref name=\"cia\" /> The country has the most religiously diverse society of all states within the Middle East, comprising 18 recognized religious sects.<ref name=\"state2017\"/><ref name=libcon>{{cite web|title=CRS Issue Brief for Congress: Lebanon|url=https://www.hsdl.org/?view&did=464480|publisher=The Library of Congress|accessdate=June 11, 2012|author=Alfred B. Prados|date=June 8, 2006}}</ref> But outside of Lebanon, Lebanese people (including diaspora) are mostly Christians.{{cn|date=October 2019}} It is also estimated that a large proportion of its population are refugees (1.5 million out of a bit over 6 million in 2017) which affects statistics.<ref name=\"state2017\"/> The refugees mostly Syrian or Palestinian are predominately Sunni but also includes Christians and Shia.<ref name=\"state2017\">{{cite web |title=International Religious Freedom Report for 2017 |url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/irf/religiousfreedom/index.htm?year=2017&dlid=280994 |website=www.state.gov |publisher=United States Department of State |accessdate=30 March 2019}} Cites Statistics Lebanon for most Lebanon statistics</ref>\n\nLebanon thus differs from other [[Middle East]] countries where Muslims are the overwhelming majority and more resembles [[Religion in Bosnia and Herzegovina|Bosnia-Herzegovina]] and [[Religion in Albania|Albania]], both in [[Southeastern Europe|Southeastern]] [[Europe]], in having a diverse mix of Muslims and Christians that each make up approximately half the country's population. Christians were once a majority inside Lebanon and are still a majority in the diaspora of the nearly 14 million Lebanese people living outside of Lebanon. The official constitution of Lebanon states that the president of the country must imperatively be a Maronite Christian.\n\n==Population by religious affiliation==\nNo official census has been taken since 1932, reflecting the political sensitivity in Lebanon over confessional (i.e. religious) balance.<ref name=\"CSLebanonpopulation\">{{cite web |title=Population (Lebanon) |url=https://country-studies.com/lebanon/population.html |website=Country Studies |publisher=Federal Research Division of the Library of Congress |accessdate=30 December 2019}}</ref>\nAs a result, the religious affiliation of the Lebanese population is very difficult to establish with certainty and various sources are used to get the possible estimate of the population by religious affiliation.\n\nThe following are different sources that do not pretend to be fully representative of the religious affiliation of the people of Lebanon.\n\nA 2012 study conducted by Statistics Lebanon, a Beirut-based research firm, found that Lebanon's population is estimated to be 54% [[Islam in Lebanon|Muslim]] (27% [[Shia Islam in Lebanon|Shia]]; 27% [[Sunni Islam in Lebanon|Sunni]]), 5.6% [[Druze in Lebanon|Druze]], 40.4% [[Christianity in Lebanon|Christian]] (21% [[Maronite Christianity in Lebanon|Maronite]], 8% [[Greek Orthodox Christianity in Lebanon|Greek Orthodox]], 5% [[Melkite Christianity in Lebanon|Melkite]], 6.4% other Christian denominations like [[Armenian Apostolic Church|Armenian Orthodox]], [[Armenian Catholic Church|Armenian Catholic]], [[Syriac Catholic Church|Syriac Catholic]], [[Syriac Orthodox Christians (Middle East)|Syriac Orthodox]], [[Roman Catholicism in Lebanon|Roman Catholic]], [[Chaldean Catholic Church|Chaldean]], [[Assyrian Church of the East|Assyrian]], [[Copt]]).<ref name=\"state2012\">{{cite web |title=International Religious Freedom Report for 2012: Lebanon |url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/irf/2012religiousfreedom/index.htm?dlid=208400&year=2012#wrapper |publisher=United States Department of State |accessdate=30 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe CIA World Factbook estimates (July 2017) the following: [[Islam in Lebanon|Muslim]] 57.7% (28.4% [[Shia Islam in Lebanon|Shia]], 28.7% [[Sunni Islam in Lebanon|Sunni]]), [[yay in Lebanon|]yay] 36.2% (Maronite Catholics are the largest Christian group), [[Druze in Lebanon|Druze]] 5.2%, and very small numbers of [[Zoroastrians]], [[Jews in Lebanon|Jews]], [[Baha'i Faith in Lebanon|Baha'is]], [[Buddhism in Lebanon|Buddhists]], [[Hinduism in Lebanon|Hindus]], and [[Mormons]].<ref name=\"cia\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/le.html#People|title=Middle East :: Lebanon \u2014 The World Factbook|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=Central Intelligence Agency, United States|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=11 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe [[International Foundation for Electoral Systems]] provides source for the registered voters in Lebanon for 2011<ref name=\"2011data\">{{cite web|title=Elections in Lebanon|url=https://qifanabki.files.wordpress.com/2011/10/ifes-lebanon-electoral-districts-2011.pdf|publisher=International Foundation for Electoral Systems|accessdate=9 July 2017|date=2011}}</ref> (it has to be noted that voter registration does not include people under 18 and unregistered voters) that puts the numbers as following: \n[[Sunni Islam in Lebanon|Sunni Islam]] 27.65%, [[Shia Islam in Lebanon|Shia Islam]] 27.35%,\n[[Maronite Christianity in Lebanon|Maronite Catholic]] 21.71%, [[Orthodox Christianity in Lebanon|Greek Orthodox]] 7.34%, [[Druze in Lebanon|Druze]] 5.74%, [[Melkite Christianity in Lebanon|Melkite Catholic]] 4.76%, [[Armenian Apostolic Church|Armenian Apostolic]] 2.64%, [[Minorities (Lebanon)|other Christian Minorities]] 1.28%, [[Alawites in Lebanon|Alawite Shia Islam]] 0.88%, [[Armenian Catholic]] 0.62%, [[Protestantism in Lebanon|Evangelical Protestant]] 0.53%, and other 0.18% of the population.\n\nThere is also a very small and ancient community of Zoroastrians numbering between 100-500 individuals.<ref name=\"seif\">{{cite web |title=Seif And The \u201cFire Worshipers\u201d Of Beirut? |url=https://seifandbeirut.wordpress.com/2010/10/09/seif-and-the-fire-worshipers-of-beirut/amp/ |website=Seif and his Beiruti Adventures |language=en |date=9 October 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Chebaro |first1=Mohamed |title=Lebanon\u2019s Zoroastrians want a civil state |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503092332/https://now.mmedia.me/lb/en/reportsfeatures/564417-lebanons-zoroastrians-want-a-civil-state |work=NOw (mmedia.me) |date=18 November 2014}}</ref> Lebanon also has a [[History of the Jews in Lebanon|Jewish]] population, estimated at less than 100.<ref name=\"state2017\"/>\n\n===Demographics===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  margin:0.5em 0 0.5em 1em;\"\n|+ Religious Statistics of Lebanon{{Citation needed|reason=citations are needed for each of the years|date=December 2019}}\n|-\n! Denomination\n! 1932\n! 2018\n! Growth\n! Percentage of Growth\n|-\n| [[Maronite Catholicism]] || 351,197 || 934,704 || 583,507 || 166.1% {{increase}}\n|-\n| [[Greek Orthodox Church of Antioch|Greek Orthodox Church]] || 133,343 || 381,865 || 196,522 || 186.4% {{increase}}\n|-\n| [[Melkite Greek Catholic Church|Greek Catholicism]] || 76,336 || 213,193 || 136,857 || 179.3% {{increase}}\n|-\n| [[Armenian Orthodox Church]] || 28,072 || 94,780 || 66,708 || 237.6% {{increase}}\n|-\n| [[Armenian Catholicism]] || 6,434 || 22,344 || 15,910 || 247.3% {{increase}}\n|-\n| [[Syriac Orthodox Church]] || 2,820 || 21,447 || 18,627 || 660.5% {{increase}}\n|-\n| [[Syriac Catholicism]] || 3,115 || 13,105 || 9,990 || 320.7% {{increase}}\n|-\n| [[Protestantism]] || 4,600 || 20,668 || 16,068 || 349.3% {{increase}}\n|-\n| [[Chaldean Catholic Church|Chaldean Orthodox Church and Catholicism]] || 744 || 3,594 || 2,850 || 383% {{increase}}\n|-\n| Other Christian Denominations || 6,463 || 33,275 || 26,812 || 414.8% {{increase}}\n|-\n| '''[[Christianity]]''' || '''613,124''' || '''1,538,975''' || '''925,851''' || '''183.6%''' {{increase}}\n|-\n| [[Sunni Islam]] || 394,305 || 2,121,853 || 1,727,548 || 786.1% {{increase}}\n|-\n| [[Shia Islam]] || 366,545 || 2,043,718 || 1,677,173 || 947% {{increase}}\n|-\n| [[Alawi Islam]] || 4,830 || 55,677 || 50,847 || 1,053% {{increase}}\n|-\n| '''[[Islam]]''' || '''765,680''' || '''4,164,418''' || '''3,404,738''' || '''861.6%''' {{increase}}\n|-\n| '''[[Druze|Druzism]]''' || '''62,084''' || '''295,664''' || '''233,580''' || '''376.2%''' {{increase}}\n|-\n| '''[[Judaism]]''' || '''4,003''' || '''4,805''' || '''802''' || '''20%''' {{increase}}\n|}\n\n==Geographical distribution of sects in Lebanon==\n{{multiple image\n | align = left\n\n | image1 = 1988 distribution of Lebanon's main religious groups.tif\n | width1 = 100\n | caption1 = Estimated distribution of main religious groups, 1985, by the [[CIA]]{{Citation needed|reason=a proper citation is needed not just a year|date=December 2019}}\n\n | image2 = Lebanon religious groups distribution.jpg\n | width2 = 100\n | caption2  = Lebanon religious groups distribution{{Citation needed|reason=who did this and when|date=December 2019}}\n\n | image3 = Lebanon religious groups.jpg\n | width3 = 100\n | caption3  = An estimate of the area distribution of Lebanon's main religious groups{{Citation needed|reason=who did this and when|date=December 2019}}\n\n | footer = Maps of religion distribution in Lebanon\n}}\n\n===Lebanese Muslims===\n{{Main|Islam in Lebanon}}\n[[Islam in Lebanon|Lebanese Muslims]] are divided into many sects like [[Lebanese Sunni Muslims|Sunnis]], [[Lebanese Shia Muslims|Shias]], [[Lebanese Druze|Druze]], [[Alawites in Lebanon|Alawites]], and [[Ismailis in Lebanon|Ismailis]].\n\n[[Lebanese Sunni Muslims|Lebanese Sunnis]] are mainly residents of the major cities: west [[Beirut]], [[Tripoli, Lebanon|Tripoli]], and [[Sidon]]. Sunnis are also present in rural areas including [[Akkar District|Akkar]], Ikleem al Kharoub, and the western [[Beqaa Valley]].\n\n[[Lebanese Shia Muslims|Lebanese Shias]] are concentrated in [[Southern Lebanon]], [[Baalbek District]], [[Hermel District]] and the south [[Beirut]] (southern parts of [[Greater Beirut]]).\n\n[[Lebanese Druze]] are concentrated south of Mount Lebanon, in the [[Hasbaya District]] and [[Chouf District]]. Under the Lebanese political division (Parliament of Lebanon Seat Allocation) the Druze community is designated as one of the five Lebanese Muslim communities (Sunni, Shia, Druze, Alawi, and Ismaili), despite the Druze and Muslims having very different beliefs.\n\n====Lebanese Druze====\nThe Lebanese government tend to count its [[Druze]] citizens as part of its [[Muslim]] population.{{Citation needed|reason=previous cite was almost certainly circular|date=December 2019}}\n\n===Lebanese Christians===\n{{Main|Christianity in Lebanon}}\n[[Christianity in Lebanon|Lebanese Christians]] are divided into many groups, several types of Catholics for instance the [[Maronite Christianity in Lebanon|Maronites]] and Greek Catholics (Melkites), Greek [[Orthodox Christianity in Lebanon|Orthodox]], Oriental Orthodox (among which are Syriacs, Armenians and Copts), Church of the East (Assyrians) and [[Protestantism in Lebanon|Protestants]].\n\n[[Maronite Christianity in Lebanon|Lebanese Maronites]] are concentrated in the north Beirut (northern parts of [[Greater Beirut]]), northern part of [[Mount Lebanon Governorate]], southern part of [[North Governorate]], parts of [[Beqaa Governorate]] and [[South Governorate]].<ref>[http://www.minorityrights.org/5070/lebanon/maronites.html Lebanon Maronites Overview] World Directory of Minorities. June 2008. Retrieved 28 December 2013.</ref>\n\nGreek Catholics are found everywhere but in particular in districts on the eastern slopes of the Lebanese mountain range and in Zahle where they are a majority.\n\n[[Orthodox Christianity in Lebanon|Lebanese Orthodox]] are concentrated in the north Beirut (northern parts of [[Greater Beirut]]), [[North Governorate|Lebanese North]] areas including [[Zgharta]], [[Bsharre]], [[Koura District|Koura]], and [[Batroun]].\n\n[[Protestantism in Lebanon|Lebanese Protestants]] are concentrated mainly within the area of [[Beirut]] and [[Greater Beirut]].\n\nThe other Lebanese Christians are concentrated also in similar areas like in east [[Beirut]] (northern parts of [[Greater Beirut]]), [[Mount Lebanon]], [[Zahl\u00e9]], and [[Jezzine]].\n\n===Lebanese Jews===\n{{Main|History of the Jews in Lebanon}}\n\nAs of 2018, the Jews in Lebanon make up the smallest religious group, with merely 0.08% of the population.\n\n==Current political and religious issues==\n{{Multiple issues|section=yes|\n{{Expand section|date=March 2018}}\n{{More citations needed section|date=February 2016}}\n}}\n\nUnder the terms of an agreement known as the [[National Pact]] between the various political and religious leaders of Lebanon, the [[List of Presidents of Lebanon|president of the country]] must be a [[Maronite Christianity in Lebanon|Maronite]], the [[Prime Minister of Lebanon|Prime Minister]] must be a [[Lebanese Sunni Muslims|Sunni]], and the [[List of Speakers of the Parliament of Lebanon|Speaker of Parliament]] must be a [[Lebanese Shia Muslims|Shia]].\n\nAlthough Lebanon is a [[Secularism in Lebanon|secular country]], family matters such as marriage, divorce and inheritance are still handled by the religious authorities representing a person's faith. Calls for civil marriage are unanimously rejected by the religious authorities but civil marriages conducted in another country are recognized by Lebanese civil authorities.\n\n[[Irreligion|Non-religion]] is not recognized by the state. The [[Ministry of Interior and Municipalities (Lebanon)|Minister of the Interior]] [[Ziad Baroud]] made it possible in 2009 to have the religious sect removed from the [[Lebanese identity card]]. This does not, however, deny the religious authorities complete control over civil family issues inside the country.<ref>{{cite news |title=Religious affiliation to disappear from Lebanese documents |url=http://www.asianews.it/index.php?l=en&art=14472&size=A |accessdate=30 March 2019 |work=www.asianews.it |date=13 February 2009}}</ref><ref>[http://www.barcodenation.co.uk/identity-blog/2009/02/religious-affiliation-can-be-removed-from-lebanese-id-cards/ Religious Affiliation Can Be Removed From Lebanese ID Cards]. Barcode Nation (2009-02-25). Retrieved on 2013-09-26.</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery perrow=\"7\">\nFile:Khatem_Al_Anbiyaa_Mosque_Detail.jpg|Detail of the dome of the Khatem al-Anbiyaa Mosque in downtown Beirut\nFile:ChurchMosque.jpg|[[Saint George Maronite Cathedral, Beirut|Saint George Maronite Cathedral]] and the [[Mohammad Al-Amin Mosque]], Beirut\nFile:St georges orthodox cathedral beirut.jpg|Saint George Eastern Orthodox Cathedral in downtown Beirut\nFile:St. George's Greek-Orthodox Cathedral (Beirut).JPG|[[Saint George Greek Orthodox Cathedral]] on Nejme Square\nFile:St_Elie_-_St_Gregory_Armenian_Catholic_Cathedral.jpg|[[St. Elie and St. Gregory the Illuminator Armenian Catholic Cathedral]] in Beirut\nFile:Prophet_Job_Shrine.jpg|Druze Prophet of Job Shrine\nFile:Lebanese electorate (largest community per minor district and-or qada), based on 2017 data.png|Listing the largest community in the Lebanese electorate, per ''qada'' and/or \"minor district\".<br />Green = Sunni<br />Purple = Shia<br />Blue = Druze<br />Yellow = Maronite<br />Orange = Greek Orthodox<br />Red = Armenian Orthodox\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Christianity in Lebanon]]\n* [[Islam in Lebanon]]\n* [[History of the Jews in Lebanon]]\n* [[Secularism in Lebanon]]\n* [[Irreligion in Lebanon]]\n* [[Freedom of religion in Lebanon]]\n* [[Freemasonry in Lebanon]]\n* [[Demographics of Lebanon]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Asia topic|Religion in}}\n{{Demographics of Lebanon}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Religion in Lebanon}}\n[[Category:Religion in Lebanon|*]]\n<ref> https://arabicpages.com.au/article/religion-in-lebanon.html</ref>\n", "text_old": "{{Pie chart\n|thumb = right\n|caption = Religion in Lebanon in 2012 by Statistics Lebanon<ref name=\"state2012\"/>\n|label1 = [[Sunni Islam]]\n|value1 = 27\n|color1 = LightGreen\n|label2 = [[Shia Islam]]\n|value2 = 27\n|color2 = DarkGreen\n|label3 = [[Maronite Church|Maronite Catholicism]]\n|value3 = 21\n|color3 = Red\n|label4 = [[Melkite Greek Catholic Church|Greek Catholicism]]\n|value4 = 5\n|color4 = Yellow\n|label5 = [[Greek Orthodox Church of Antioch|Greek Orthodoxy]]\n|value5 = 8\n|color5 = Purple\n|label6 = Other Christian ([[Armenian Apostolic Church|Armenian Apostolic]] and others)\n|value6 = 6.5\n|color6 = DarkBlue\n|label7 = [[Druze]]\n|value7 = 5.6\n|color7 = Violet\n|label8 = Other\n|value8 = 1\n|color8 = Black\n}}\n'''[[Lebanon]]''' is an eastern Mediterranean country that is composed of mostly [[Muslim Arabs|Muslims]] and [[Christians]].<ref name=\"cia\" />   The main two religions are [[Islam in Lebanon|Islam]] with 50% of the citizens ([[Sunni Islam in Lebanon|Sunni]] and [[Shia Islam in Lebanon|Shia]]) and [[Christianity in Lebanon|Christianity]] with 44.4% of the citizens (the [[Maronite Christianity in Lebanon|Maronite Church]], the [[Greek Orthodox Christianity in Lebanon|Orthodox Church]], the [[Melkite Greek Catholic Church]], the [[Protestantism in Lebanon|Protestant Church]], the [[Armenian Apostolic Church]]). The [[Druze in Lebanon|Druze]] are about 4.9% of the citizens.<ref name=\"cia\" /> The country has the most religiously diverse society of all states within the Middle East, comprising 18 recognized religious sects.<ref name=\"state2017\"/><ref name=libcon>{{cite web|title=CRS Issue Brief for Congress: Lebanon|url=https://www.hsdl.org/?view&did=464480|publisher=The Library of Congress|accessdate=June 11, 2012|author=Alfred B. Prados|date=June 8, 2006}}</ref> But outside of Lebanon, Lebanese people (including diaspora) are mostly Christians.{{cn|date=October 2019}} It is also estimated that a large proportion of its population are refugees (1.5 million out of a bit over 6 million in 2017) which affects statistics.<ref name=\"state2017\"/> The refugees mostly Syrian or Palestinian are predominately Sunni but also includes Christians and Shia.<ref name=\"state2017\">{{cite web |title=International Religious Freedom Report for 2017 |url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/irf/religiousfreedom/index.htm?year=2017&dlid=280994 |website=www.state.gov |publisher=United States Department of State |accessdate=30 March 2019}} Cites Statistics Lebanon for most Lebanon statistics</ref>\n\nLebanon thus differs from other [[Middle East]] countries where Muslims are the overwhelming majority and more resembles [[Religion in Bosnia and Herzegovina|Bosnia-Herzegovina]] and [[Religion in Albania|Albania]], both in [[Southeastern Europe|Southeastern]] [[Europe]], in having a diverse mix of Muslims and Christians that each make up approximately half the country's population. Christians were once a majority inside Lebanon and are still a majority in the diaspora of the nearly 14 million Lebanese people living outside of Lebanon. The official constitution of Lebanon states that the president of the country must imperatively be a Maronite Christian.\n\n==Population by religious affiliation==\nNo official census has been taken since 1932, reflecting the political sensitivity in Lebanon over confessional (i.e. religious) balance.<ref name=\"CSLebanonpopulation\">{{cite web |title=Population (Lebanon) |url=https://country-studies.com/lebanon/population.html |website=Country Studies |publisher=Federal Research Division of the Library of Congress |accessdate=30 December 2019}}</ref>\nAs a result, the religious affiliation of the Lebanese population is very difficult to establish with certainty and various sources are used to get the possible estimate of the population by religious affiliation.\n\nThe following are different sources that do not pretend to be fully representative of the religious affiliation of the people of Lebanon.\n\nA 2012 study conducted by Statistics Lebanon, a Beirut-based research firm, found that Lebanon's population is estimated to be 54% [[Islam in Lebanon|Muslim]] (27% [[Shia Islam in Lebanon|Shia]]; 27% [[Sunni Islam in Lebanon|Sunni]]), 5.6% [[Druze in Lebanon|Druze]], 40.4% [[Christianity in Lebanon|Christian]] (21% [[Maronite Christianity in Lebanon|Maronite]], 8% [[Greek Orthodox Christianity in Lebanon|Greek Orthodox]], 5% [[Melkite Christianity in Lebanon|Melkite]], 6.4% other Christian denominations like [[Armenian Apostolic Church|Armenian Orthodox]], [[Armenian Catholic Church|Armenian Catholic]], [[Syriac Catholic Church|Syriac Catholic]], [[Syriac Orthodox Christians (Middle East)|Syriac Orthodox]], [[Roman Catholicism in Lebanon|Roman Catholic]], [[Chaldean Catholic Church|Chaldean]], [[Assyrian Church of the East|Assyrian]], [[Copt]]).<ref name=\"state2012\">{{cite web |title=International Religious Freedom Report for 2012: Lebanon |url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/irf/2012religiousfreedom/index.htm?dlid=208400&year=2012#wrapper |publisher=United States Department of State |accessdate=30 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe CIA World Factbook estimates (July 2017) the following: [[Islam in Lebanon|Muslim]] 57.7% (28.4% [[Shia Islam in Lebanon|Shia]], 28.7% [[Sunni Islam in Lebanon|Sunni]]), [[Christianity in Lebanon|Christian]] 36.2% (Maronite Catholics are the largest Christian group), [[Druze in Lebanon|Druze]] 5.2%, and very small numbers of [[Zoroastrians]], [[Jews in Lebanon|Jews]], [[Baha'i Faith in Lebanon|Baha'is]], [[Buddhism in Lebanon|Buddhists]], [[Hinduism in Lebanon|Hindus]], and [[Mormons]].<ref name=\"cia\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/le.html#People|title=Middle East :: Lebanon \u2014 The World Factbook|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=Central Intelligence Agency, United States|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=11 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe [[International Foundation for Electoral Systems]] provides source for the registered voters in Lebanon for 2011<ref name=\"2011data\">{{cite web|title=Elections in Lebanon|url=https://qifanabki.files.wordpress.com/2011/10/ifes-lebanon-electoral-districts-2011.pdf|publisher=International Foundation for Electoral Systems|accessdate=9 July 2017|date=2011}}</ref> (it has to be noted that voter registration does not include people under 18 and unregistered voters) that puts the numbers as following: \n[[Sunni Islam in Lebanon|Sunni Islam]] 27.65%, [[Shia Islam in Lebanon|Shia Islam]] 27.35%,\n[[Maronite Christianity in Lebanon|Maronite Catholic]] 21.71%, [[Orthodox Christianity in Lebanon|Greek Orthodox]] 7.34%, [[Druze in Lebanon|Druze]] 5.74%, [[Melkite Christianity in Lebanon|Melkite Catholic]] 4.76%, [[Armenian Apostolic Church|Armenian Apostolic]] 2.64%, [[Minorities (Lebanon)|other Christian Minorities]] 1.28%, [[Alawites in Lebanon|Alawite Shia Islam]] 0.88%, [[Armenian Catholic]] 0.62%, [[Protestantism in Lebanon|Evangelical Protestant]] 0.53%, and other 0.18% of the population.\n\nThere is also a very small and ancient community of Zoroastrians numbering between 100-500 individuals.<ref name=\"seif\">{{cite web |title=Seif And The \u201cFire Worshipers\u201d Of Beirut? |url=https://seifandbeirut.wordpress.com/2010/10/09/seif-and-the-fire-worshipers-of-beirut/amp/ |website=Seif and his Beiruti Adventures |language=en |date=9 October 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Chebaro |first1=Mohamed |title=Lebanon\u2019s Zoroastrians want a civil state |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503092332/https://now.mmedia.me/lb/en/reportsfeatures/564417-lebanons-zoroastrians-want-a-civil-state |work=NOw (mmedia.me) |date=18 November 2014}}</ref> Lebanon also has a [[History of the Jews in Lebanon|Jewish]] population, estimated at less than 100.<ref name=\"state2017\"/>\n\n===Demographics===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  margin:0.5em 0 0.5em 1em;\"\n|+ Religious Statistics of Lebanon{{Citation needed|reason=citations are needed for each of the years|date=December 2019}}\n|-\n! Denomination\n! 1932\n! 2018\n! Growth\n! Percentage of Growth\n|-\n| [[Maronite Catholicism]] || 351,197 || 934,704 || 583,507 || 166.1% {{increase}}\n|-\n| [[Greek Orthodox Church of Antioch|Greek Orthodox Church]] || 133,343 || 381,865 || 196,522 || 186.4% {{increase}}\n|-\n| [[Melkite Greek Catholic Church|Greek Catholicism]] || 76,336 || 213,193 || 136,857 || 179.3% {{increase}}\n|-\n| [[Armenian Orthodox Church]] || 28,072 || 94,780 || 66,708 || 237.6% {{increase}}\n|-\n| [[Armenian Catholicism]] || 6,434 || 22,344 || 15,910 || 247.3% {{increase}}\n|-\n| [[Syriac Orthodox Church]] || 2,820 || 21,447 || 18,627 || 660.5% {{increase}}\n|-\n| [[Syriac Catholicism]] || 3,115 || 13,105 || 9,990 || 320.7% {{increase}}\n|-\n| [[Protestantism]] || 4,600 || 20,668 || 16,068 || 349.3% {{increase}}\n|-\n| [[Chaldean Catholic Church|Chaldean Orthodox Church and Catholicism]] || 744 || 3,594 || 2,850 || 383% {{increase}}\n|-\n| Other Christian Denominations || 6,463 || 33,275 || 26,812 || 414.8% {{increase}}\n|-\n| '''[[Christianity]]''' || '''613,124''' || '''1,538,975''' || '''925,851''' || '''183.6%''' {{increase}}\n|-\n| [[Sunni Islam]] || 394,305 || 2,121,853 || 1,727,548 || 786.1% {{increase}}\n|-\n| [[Shia Islam]] || 366,545 || 2,043,718 || 1,677,173 || 947% {{increase}}\n|-\n| [[Alawi Islam]] || 4,830 || 55,677 || 50,847 || 1,053% {{increase}}\n|-\n| '''[[Islam]]''' || '''765,680''' || '''4,164,418''' || '''3,404,738''' || '''861.6%''' {{increase}}\n|-\n| '''[[Druze|Druzism]]''' || '''62,084''' || '''295,664''' || '''233,580''' || '''376.2%''' {{increase}}\n|-\n| '''[[Judaism]]''' || '''4,003''' || '''4,805''' || '''802''' || '''20%''' {{increase}}\n|}\n\n==Geographical distribution of sects in Lebanon==\n{{multiple image\n | align = left\n\n | image1 = 1988 distribution of Lebanon's main religious groups.tif\n | width1 = 100\n | caption1 = Estimated distribution of main religious groups, 1985, by the [[CIA]]{{Citation needed|reason=a proper citation is needed not just a year|date=December 2019}}\n\n | image2 = Lebanon religious groups distribution.jpg\n | width2 = 100\n | caption2  = Lebanon religious groups distribution{{Citation needed|reason=who did this and when|date=December 2019}}\n\n | image3 = Lebanon religious groups.jpg\n | width3 = 100\n | caption3  = An estimate of the area distribution of Lebanon's main religious groups{{Citation needed|reason=who did this and when|date=December 2019}}\n\n | footer = Maps of religion distribution in Lebanon\n}}\n\n===Lebanese Muslims===\n{{Main|Islam in Lebanon}}\n[[Islam in Lebanon|Lebanese Muslims]] are divided into many sects like [[Lebanese Sunni Muslims|Sunnis]], [[Lebanese Shia Muslims|Shias]], [[Lebanese Druze|Druze]], [[Alawites in Lebanon|Alawites]], and [[Ismailis in Lebanon|Ismailis]].\n\n[[Lebanese Sunni Muslims|Lebanese Sunnis]] are mainly residents of the major cities: west [[Beirut]], [[Tripoli, Lebanon|Tripoli]], and [[Sidon]]. Sunnis are also present in rural areas including [[Akkar District|Akkar]], Ikleem al Kharoub, and the western [[Beqaa Valley]].\n\n[[Lebanese Shia Muslims|Lebanese Shias]] are concentrated in [[Southern Lebanon]], [[Baalbek District]], [[Hermel District]] and the south [[Beirut]] (southern parts of [[Greater Beirut]]).\n\n[[Lebanese Druze]] are concentrated south of Mount Lebanon, in the [[Hasbaya District]] and [[Chouf District]]. Under the Lebanese political division (Parliament of Lebanon Seat Allocation) the Druze community is designated as one of the five Lebanese Muslim communities (Sunni, Shia, Druze, Alawi, and Ismaili), despite the Druze and Muslims having very different beliefs.\n\n====Lebanese Druze====\nThe Lebanese government tend to count its [[Druze]] citizens as part of its [[Muslim]] population.{{Citation needed|reason=previous cite was almost certainly circular|date=December 2019}}\n\n===Lebanese Christians===\n{{Main|Christianity in Lebanon}}\n[[Christianity in Lebanon|Lebanese Christians]] are divided into many groups, several types of Catholics for instance the [[Maronite Christianity in Lebanon|Maronites]] and Greek Catholics (Melkites), Greek [[Orthodox Christianity in Lebanon|Orthodox]], Oriental Orthodox (among which are Syriacs, Armenians and Copts), Church of the East (Assyrians) and [[Protestantism in Lebanon|Protestants]].\n\n[[Maronite Christianity in Lebanon|Lebanese Maronites]] are concentrated in the north Beirut (northern parts of [[Greater Beirut]]), northern part of [[Mount Lebanon Governorate]], southern part of [[North Governorate]], parts of [[Beqaa Governorate]] and [[South Governorate]].<ref>[http://www.minorityrights.org/5070/lebanon/maronites.html Lebanon Maronites Overview] World Directory of Minorities. June 2008. Retrieved 28 December 2013.</ref>\n\nGreek Catholics are found everywhere but in particular in districts on the eastern slopes of the Lebanese mountain range and in Zahle where they are a majority.\n\n[[Orthodox Christianity in Lebanon|Lebanese Orthodox]] are concentrated in the north Beirut (northern parts of [[Greater Beirut]]), [[North Governorate|Lebanese North]] areas including [[Zgharta]], [[Bsharre]], [[Koura District|Koura]], and [[Batroun]].\n\n[[Protestantism in Lebanon|Lebanese Protestants]] are concentrated mainly within the area of [[Beirut]] and [[Greater Beirut]].\n\nThe other Lebanese Christians are concentrated also in similar areas like in east [[Beirut]] (northern parts of [[Greater Beirut]]), [[Mount Lebanon]], [[Zahl\u00e9]], and [[Jezzine]].\n\n===Lebanese Jews===\n{{Main|History of the Jews in Lebanon}}\n\nAs of 2018, the Jews in Lebanon make up the smallest religious group, with merely 0.08% of the population.\n\n==Current political and religious issues==\n{{Multiple issues|section=yes|\n{{Expand section|date=March 2018}}\n{{More citations needed section|date=February 2016}}\n}}\n\nUnder the terms of an agreement known as the [[National Pact]] between the various political and religious leaders of Lebanon, the [[List of Presidents of Lebanon|president of the country]] must be a [[Maronite Christianity in Lebanon|Maronite]], the [[Prime Minister of Lebanon|Prime Minister]] must be a [[Lebanese Sunni Muslims|Sunni]], and the [[List of Speakers of the Parliament of Lebanon|Speaker of Parliament]] must be a [[Lebanese Shia Muslims|Shia]].\n\nAlthough Lebanon is a [[Secularism in Lebanon|secular country]], family matters such as marriage, divorce and inheritance are still handled by the religious authorities representing a person's faith. Calls for civil marriage are unanimously rejected by the religious authorities but civil marriages conducted in another country are recognized by Lebanese civil authorities.\n\n[[Irreligion|Non-religion]] is not recognized by the state. The [[Ministry of Interior and Municipalities (Lebanon)|Minister of the Interior]] [[Ziad Baroud]] made it possible in 2009 to have the religious sect removed from the [[Lebanese identity card]]. This does not, however, deny the religious authorities complete control over civil family issues inside the country.<ref>{{cite news |title=Religious affiliation to disappear from Lebanese documents |url=http://www.asianews.it/index.php?l=en&art=14472&size=A |accessdate=30 March 2019 |work=www.asianews.it |date=13 February 2009}}</ref><ref>[http://www.barcodenation.co.uk/identity-blog/2009/02/religious-affiliation-can-be-removed-from-lebanese-id-cards/ Religious Affiliation Can Be Removed From Lebanese ID Cards]. Barcode Nation (2009-02-25). Retrieved on 2013-09-26.</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery perrow=\"7\">\nFile:Khatem_Al_Anbiyaa_Mosque_Detail.jpg|Detail of the dome of the Khatem al-Anbiyaa Mosque in downtown Beirut\nFile:ChurchMosque.jpg|[[Saint George Maronite Cathedral, Beirut|Saint George Maronite Cathedral]] and the [[Mohammad Al-Amin Mosque]], Beirut\nFile:St georges orthodox cathedral beirut.jpg|Saint George Eastern Orthodox Cathedral in downtown Beirut\nFile:St. George's Greek-Orthodox Cathedral (Beirut).JPG|[[Saint George Greek Orthodox Cathedral]] on Nejme Square\nFile:St_Elie_-_St_Gregory_Armenian_Catholic_Cathedral.jpg|[[St. Elie and St. Gregory the Illuminator Armenian Catholic Cathedral]] in Beirut\nFile:Prophet_Job_Shrine.jpg|Druze Prophet of Job Shrine\nFile:Lebanese electorate (largest community per minor district and-or qada), based on 2017 data.png|Listing the largest community in the Lebanese electorate, per ''qada'' and/or \"minor district\".<br />Green = Sunni<br />Purple = Shia<br />Blue = Druze<br />Yellow = Maronite<br />Orange = Greek Orthodox<br />Red = Armenian Orthodox\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Christianity in Lebanon]]\n* [[Islam in Lebanon]]\n* [[History of the Jews in Lebanon]]\n